95–1232","1224–1258":"1224–1258","1179–Male":"1179–Afdød","1180–Female":"1180–Afdød","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1232":"1232","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England"},"nl":{"1204–1224":"1204–1224","1195–1232":"1195–1232","1224–1258":"1224–1258","1179–Male":"1179–Overleden","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1232":"1232","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1204–1224":"1204–1224","1195–1232":"1195–1232","1224–1258":"1224–1258","1179–Male":"1179–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1232":"1232","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Randulph","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: from <i>Randolf</i>, an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>rand</i> ‘rim (of a shield), shield’ + <i>wolf</i> ‘wolf’. This was introduced into England by the Normans in Old French forms of two different ancient Germanic personal names which became confused with each other: <i>Randulf</i> (from <i>rand</i> ‘(shield-)edge’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’) and <i>Rannulf</i> (from <i>hraf(a)n</i> ‘raven’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’).","History: An American family bearing this surname are descended from William Randolph (<i>c.</i> 1651–1711), a planter and merchant, a member of a family that originally came from Sussex, England. William Randolph emigrated from Warwickshire to VA <i>c.</i> 1673. He was a forebear of Thomas Jefferson and Robert E. Lee. Randolph had seven sons, each of whom inherited an estate, the name of which was sometimes added to their own, such as Sir John Randolph of Tazewell. His great-grandsons included Edmund Randolph (1753–1813), first attorney general of the US and one of the framers of the US Constitution, and the diplomat and statesman John Randolph of Roanoke (1773–1833), who served as US minister to Russia."],"variants":[{"name":"Rand","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Rand</i>, a pet form of <i>Randolf</i>. Compare   Randolph  ,   Randall  ,   Randy  , and see also   Rance  .","English: habitational name from Rand (Lincolnshire), Rand Grange (North Yorkshire), or Raunds (Northamptonshire), all of which derive from Old English <i>rand</i> ‘edge, border, rim’.","German: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound personal names formed with <i>rand</i> ‘rim (of a shield)’. Compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Randerson","meanings":["English (West and East Yorkshire): patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Randolf</i> (see   Randolph  ) + <i>-son</i>. In East Anglia the name may also have been influenced by a form of the now rare or extinct <b>Rendlesham</b>, itself from the place of that name in Suffolk. The placename probably derives from an Old English personal name <i>Rendel</i> (genitive <i>Rendeles</i>) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."]},{"name":"Randolf","meanings":["English and German: variant of   Randolph  ."]},{"name":"Randall","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): common colloquial pronunciation of   Randolph  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":11,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":20,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Randulph was born in 1204, in Harley, Shropshire, England, her father, Robert Randulph, was 26 and her mother, Mrs Robert Randulph, was 25. She had at least 1 son with Nicholas de Harley. She died in 1224, in her hometown, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1204–1224":"1204–1224","1195–1232":"1195–1232","1224–1258":"1224–1258","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1232":"1232","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1204–1224":"1204–1224","1195–1232":"1195–1232","1224–1258":"1224–1258","1179–Male":"1179–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1204":"1204","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1232":"1232","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1204–1224":"1204–1224","1195–123